'''Geçitkale Air Base''' {{Airport codes|GEC|LCGK|}} is a [[military airfield]] of the [[Turkish Air Force]] near [[Lefkoniko]] ({{lang-tr|Geçitkale|links=no}}) in [[Northern Cyprus]]. Construction was completed around 1990. During the renovation of the [[Ercan International Airport]] between September 2002 and May 2004, it served as Northern Cyprus' primary civilian airport.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ercan Havaalanı 10 Mayıs'ta açılıyo|url=http://hurarsiv.hurriyet.com.tr/goster/haber.aspx?id=223525|publisher=Hürriyet|date=6 May 2004|accessdate=11 February 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref> Geçitkale's unofficial [[International Civil Aviation Organization airport code|ICAO code]] is LCGK.<ref name="aip">{{cite web|title=AD 2 – Gecitkale|url=http://www.kktculastirma.org/shava_mev/doc/gecitkale.pdf|website=TRNC AIP|accessdate=13 February 2015|date=2 September 2004}}</ref>
In the summer of 1998, amid rising tensions between Greece and Turkey, Turkey briefly stationed six [[F-16]]s at Geçitkale, in response to the former's positioning of four F-16s and two [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] at [[Paphos International Airport|Paphos]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clogg|first1=Richard|title=A Concise History of Greece|date=2013|location=Cambridge University Press|page=229|edition=3rd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M492AgAAQBAJ}}</ref> Combat aircraft last visited the airport in November 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geçitkale|url=http://www.forgottenairfields.com/cyprus/famagusta/gecitkale-s58.html|website=Abandoned, Forgotten & Little-Known Airfields in Europe|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>
==Aerodrome characteristics== Geçitkale's only runway, 9/27, measures {{convert|2850|m|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|45|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide. In addition, there is a {{convert|285|m|abbr=on}} long [[stopway]] on either end. The airport is equipped with a [[VOR/DME]] and an [[non-directional beacon|NDB]] station.<ref name="aip"/>
